<font color="#FF0000">GOVERNMENT AND THE MILITARY</font><br>
<tt>Wed Apr  2 15:17:21 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The purpose of any military is to kill people and break things, to put it bluntly. We did not do that in Vietnam. My father served at Cam Rahn and was often frustrated about how the war was being fought while he was there. He recalls more political red tape than can possibly be mentioned here. The point I am trying to make, is that when we commit U.S. soldiers to combat, we should let the military run the war, not the government. Johnson picked bombing targets on a daily basis during the war; he should not have been doing this. It is up to the government to decide whether to commit U.S. troops to any conflict, and it is up to the military to figure out how to achieve the objectives laid before them by the government. No politician could possibly know enough about the military to effectively run a war and a country at the same time. Leave the fighting up to the military!
<p><code>-- lhsmith@zoo.uvm.edu  (Leon Smith) </code><p>


